The nobler spirits of antiquity, it hardly need be said, had higher dreams of a future state than this. For them, no more than for us, was it possible to rest in the con- viction that their brief and troubled career on earth was to be the “be all and the end all '' of existence, or that those whom they had loved and lost in death became thenceforth as though they had never been. It is idle to draw, as is often done, a different conclusion from such phrases as that after death we are a shadow and mere dust, “pulvis et umbra sumus! Horace and Shakespeare both believed in an immor- tality‚ but it was an immortality different in its kind.
